index 0000000..1da2282
--- /dev/null
+++ b/ROOT-SECURITY-RELEASE.md
@@ -0,0 +1,90 @@
+# Security Advisory False Positives
+
+This file records published CVEs/GHSAs against upstream `vm2` that were investigated
+against this fork (currently based on `3.9.17`, patched forward through the entries
+in `CHANGELOG.md`) and determined **not to apply**, along with the evidence for that
+determination.
+
+Each entry lists a "re-check trigger" — a condition under which the determination
+must be revisited. If this codebase is ever modified in a way that touches the
+described code paths, re-run the verification steps below before trusting the
+"not applicable" conclusion again.
+
+---
+
+## CVE-2026-44009 / GHSA-9vg3-4rfj-wgcm
+
+**Status:** Not applicable to this fork. No code changes made.
+
+**Upstream summary:** "Sandbox breakout via null-proto throw / `handleException`."
+A sandbox-created object with no prototype (`{__proto__: null}`), when thrown and
+caught, or used as a Promise resolution/rejection value, could be wrapped by the
+bridge's `from()` helper in a way that treated it as a host-realm object. The
+resulting proxy's `set` trap then unwrapped any sandbox-side reference to a host
+function written onto it (e.g. `e.f = Buffer.prototype.inspect`) back to the raw
+host function and stored it on the underlying object — which was actually the
+sandbox's own object, readable directly via the original sandbox reference,
+bypassing the proxy entirely. `rawHostFn.constructor` then yields the real host
+`Function` constructor → RCE.
+
+**Root cause in upstream vm2:** An earlier upstream hardening commit (`b57ac2d`,
+made for a different advisory, GHSA-mpf8-4hx2-7cjg) changed `handleException` and
+the sandbox-side `Promise.prototype.then` `onFulfilled` wrapper to use `bridge.from()`
+instead of `bridge.ensureThis()`, for symmetry with a fix elsewhere. `from()`
+unconditionally builds a wrapping proxy for any value with no recognized
+prototype, on the assumption that such a value must be host-realm. That assumption
+is false for a sandbox-created null-proto object, and is exactly what this CVE
+(GHSA-9vg3-4rfj-wgcm) fixes by reverting those two call sites back to `ensureThis()`.
+
+**Why it doesn't apply to this fork:** This fork never carried the `b57ac2d`
+commit, or the `from()`-based `handleException` it introduced. This fork's
+`handleException` (added independently in `lib/setup-sandbox.js` for
+CVE-2026-26332 / GHSA-55hx-c926-fr95) was written using `ensureThis()` from the
+start. `ensureThis()` returns a value with no recognized prototype **unchanged**
+— it never builds a wrapping proxy for such values — so the specific bug pattern
+this CVE fixes does not exist in this fork's `handleException`.
+
+This fork also does not have an `onFulfilled` wrapper on `Promise.prototype.then`
+at all (only `onRejected`, added for CVE-2026-24120), and never implemented the
+`setHostPromiseSanitizers` / host-Promise-boundary sanitization feature that the
+second vulnerable call site in upstream depended on.
+
+**Call sites using `from()`/`bridge.from()` in this fork, and why each is safe**
+(as of the version this file was written against):
+
+| Location | Value wrapped | Why it's safe |
+|---|---|---|
