+**Upstream summary:** "Promise species hijack in the `localPromise` swallow tail."
+Upstream's `localPromise` (a `class localPromise extends globalPromise` introduced
+by a separate, unrequested hardening commit, GHSA-hw58-p9xv-2mjh) attaches an
+internal "swallow tail" to every sandbox-constructed Promise, inside its own
+constructor: `apply(globalPromisePrototypeThen, this, [undefined,
+localPromiseSwallow])`. This call invokes the cached *native* host
+`Promise.prototype.then` on `this` — and host `then` resolves its downstream child
+via the species protocol (`SpeciesConstructor(this, %Promise%)`, i.e. it reads
+`this.constructor[Symbol.species]`). Every sibling call site that touches a host
+`then` (the `.then`/`.catch` overrides, the `Reflect.apply` wrapper) already
+bookends the call with `resetPromiseSpecies(this)` to pin the species to
+`localPromise`; the swallow-tail call inside the constructor was the one site that
+didn't. A sandbox subclass — `class FakePromise extends Promise { static get
+[Symbol.species]() { return ct } }` with `new FakePromise(r => r())` — hijacks the
+downstream child's constructor to a user function `ct`, which receives V8's
+internal `(resolve, reject)` capability and re-binds it to sandbox-controlled
+collectors. Combined with the "deep recursion + `e.stack`" primitive (used in
+several other CVEs in this series) to produce a genuine host-realm `RangeError`,
+the raw host error reaches the sandbox collector unsanitized, and
+`ex.constructor.constructor("return process")()` yields RCE.
+
+**Why it doesn't apply to this fork:** This fork's `localPromise` (in
+`lib/setup-sandbox.js`) is `Promise: localPromise` destructured directly from
+`global` — the plain native sandbox-realm `Promise`, not a subclass, with no
+custom constructor and no "swallow tail" mechanism at all. There is no code
+anywhere in this fork that automatically invokes a host `.then()` call as a side
+effect of constructing a Promise, so the specific hook this CVE's exploit hijacks
+(the swallow-tail call inside `localPromise`'s constructor) does not exist to be
+hijacked.
+
+This fork does have one other call site that invokes the native host `.then()`
+directly — `sanitizeAsyncIteratorResultPromise` in the CVE-2026-45411 /
+GHSA-248r-7h7q-cr24 async-generator fix (`apply(globalPromisePrototypeThen,
+promise, [...])`). Upstream's own "Considered Attack Surfaces" analysis for this
+exact advisory explicitly addresses that call site and concludes it is *not*
+vulnerable to the same pattern: the `promise` there is created internally by V8's
+async generator machinery via `NewPromiseCapability(%Promise%)` (spec-mandated to
+use the intrinsic constructor directly, bypassing species resolution for its own
+creation), and sandbox code never obtains a reference to it before this fork's
+sanitization wraps it — so there is no window for sandbox code to install a
+malicious `.constructor`/`[Symbol.species]` on it beforehand.
+
+**Verification performed:**
+1. Statically confirmed `localPromise` is `global.Promise` directly (no
+   subclass, no constructor override, no `localPromiseSwallow`-equivalent
+   anywhere in `lib/setup-sandbox.js`).
+2. Ran the canonical PoC setup directly: constructed
