vm2 NodeVM sandbox escape / RCE -- patch bypass of GHSA-8hg8-63c5-gwmx. A NodeVM
constructed with a truthy `nesting` combined with anything other than a real
`require` config object (falsy/omitted require, or truthy non-object require)
produces a NESTING_OVERRIDE-only resolver whose sole builtin is `vm2` -- a pure
escape primitive. Sandbox code does `require('vm2')`, builds an inner NodeVM
with attacker-chosen `require` config, and reaches `child_process` for host RCE.

Structural fix in lib/nodevm.js: destructure options first, then reject any
truthy `nesting` unless `requireOpts` is a non-null object or a `Resolver`
instance. The documented escape hatch (truthy `nesting` + explicit `require`
config object, even `{}`) is preserved.

Superset of upstream commits:
  01a7552add345d5a6862623884e6b79a85bf0568  fix(GHSA-m4wx-m65x-ghrr): close NESTING_OVERRIDE resolver for falsy/omitted require
  86ab819f202c3a8dad88cef5705f2e416c5188d7  fix(GHSA-m4wx-m65x-ghrr): widen NESTING_OVERRIDE guard to all input shapes

86ab819 supersedes 01a7552 in the overlapping lib/nodevm.js region; the widened
guard is used. Adaptations for 3.9.17: (a) `Resolver` is imported directly from
`./resolver` (target's `lib/main.js` does not re-export it, but `lib/resolver.js`
exports it at line 880); (b) target still uses `resolverFromOptions` rather than
the later rename to `makeResolverFromLegacyOptions` -- semantics are identical
for the guard's purposes (both hit the `if (!options)` branch on falsy input and
destructure non-object truthy input to all-undefined).

Test hunks omitted from this backport. The npm registry tarball
`vm2-3.9.17.tgz` ships only `lib/` + package metadata (per `package.json`
`files:["lib/","bin/","index.js","index.d.ts"]`) -- no `test/` directory
exists in the artifact this patch is applied to, so any `test/*` hunks would
fail with "can't find file to patch" in the pipeline. The upstream regression
suite (test/ghsa/GHSA-m4wx-m65x-ghrr/repro.js + the test/nodevm.js `nesting`
adjustment) lives on the source-repo branch and is not part of the distributed
package. The security fix in `lib/nodevm.js` stands alone: construction throws
before any insecure resolver can be built, closing every documented input shape
(falsy/omitted require, truthy non-object require, truthy non-`true` nesting).

